Distracted driving is one of the most common causes of car accidents. This includes drivers who are distracted by their phones, music, or other passengers in the car. It also includes drivers who are distracted by the road ahead, such as a construction site or a school zone.
Distracted driving can lead to accidents in a number of ways. For example, a distracted driver may not notice a red light or a stop sign and run a red light or stop sign, causing an accident. A distracted driver may also miss a turn or a lane change and crash into something.

Speeding can lead to accidents in a number of ways. For example, a speeding driver may lose control of the car and crash into something. A speeding driver may also fail to stop at a red light or stop sign and crash into something.

Failing to yield the right of way can lead to accidents in a number of ways. For example, a driver may fail to yield the right of way at a four-way stop and crash into another car. A driver may also fail to yield the right of way at a red light or a stop sign and crash into something.

Inexperienced drivers can lead to accidents in a number of ways. For example, an inexperienced driver may not know how to handle a curve in the road and crash into something. An inexperienced driver may also drive too fast or too slow for the road conditions and cause an accident.
